
[1]anthem

   AN'THEM, n. [Gr. against, and a hymn, from to sing. See Hymn.]

   A hymn sung in alternate parts; but in modern usage, a sacred tune or
   piece of music set to words, taken from the psalms or other parts of
   the scriptures, first introduced into church service in Elizabeth's
   reign.
